                    <desc>
                        <p type="site-data" source="#bibl000299b-1">
                            The remaining foundation of what once was the Xinzhu Liangyin Hall 心珠朗瑩殿, also known as the Great Hall大殿. The structure that once stood on the foundation was destroyed during the <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Republican Period</term> leaving the <term ref="/place/000299c">Jingangbaozuo Pagoda 金刚宝座塔</term> as the last complete remaining extent building on the site. The original Xinzhu Liangyin Hall was five or six zhang 丈, or between about 16.65 and 19.98 meters, in height (Wang 1997). (Beijing shi wenwu ju 2008, vol. 1, 256) (Xu 2010)
                        </p>
                        <p type="site-data">
                            Upon southern entry to <term ref="/place/000299">Zhenjue Monastery 真覺寺</term>, the remains of the Xinzhu Liangyin Hall’s foundation is in the center of the path and directly centered before <term ref="/place/000299c">Jingangbaozuo Pagoda</term>. The remains can be circumnavigated.
                        </p>
                        <p type="site-data">
                            The remains of the Xinzhu Liangyin Hall’s foundation are made of cut stone and is elevated on a platform. The foundation is rectangular in shape with the southern facing foundation having openings adjacent to the southeast and southwestern corners.  The stone foundation is extensively carved and resembles a highly stylized wall. The top third and bottom third of the wall protrude slightly form the middle third. The top of the protruding bottom third of the wall has a lotus petal motif that continues along the entire foundation. Each corner of the middle section contains a stylized pillar interspaced with inscribed images. The bottom of the top protruding third contains bracketing that resembles lotus petals.  The top eight of the foundation protrudes slightly more than the rest and is inscribed with Sanskrit characters. The style of Xinzhu Liangyin Hall’s foundation is comparable to the style of the bottom levels of the foundation of <term ref="/place/000299c">Jingangbaozuo Pagoda</term>.                            
                        </p>
